(12, 'Bharatpur-Bardaghat 220 KV power transmission line project', '27.6996', '84.4340.0', 'This case concerns the construction of the transmission line between Hetauda-Bharatpur and Bharatpur-Bardaghat. It crosses the border between India and Nepal,  with a capacity of up to 1000 MW, between the two states.  It connects to the existing 132 kV transmission line at Arun Khola.', 'This case concerns the construction of the transmission line between Hetauda-Bharatpur and Bharatpur-Bardaghat. It crosses the border between India and Nepal, in order to <a href=\"https://www.lahurnip.org/world-bank-financed-220-kv-transmission-line-project\">facilitate electricity trade</a> with a capacity of up to 1000 MW, between the two states.  It connects to the existing 132 kV transmission line at Arun Khola. The primary area of concern is the human settlement of Binayi Tribeni Rural Municipality of Nawalparasi district, Gandaki province. The overall budget for the project is approximately <a href=\"https://kathmandupost.com/money/2019/10/15/electricity-authority-looking-for-new-contractor-to-build-transmission-line\">$182 million</a>, $99 million of this being a concessional loan from the World Bank’s International Development Association, and the rest of the funding coming from the Nepalese government.  The construction of the final two towers of the transmission line was halted due to an interim order of the Supreme Court, following a writ petition filed by locals. The affected communities, with the help of LAHURNIP, <a href=\"https://risingnepaldaily.com/news/13228#:~:text=The%20Bharatpur-Bardaghat%20132%20kV%20transmission%20line%20is%20separated,the%20old%20132%20KV%20line%20to%20Bardaghat%20substation\">filed legal litigation</a> stating their objection to the change in plans for the towers’ location, and the impact it would have on indigenous communities, who had not been properly consulted by the Nepal Electricity Authority.  They demanded that the route be changed back to the original plans, which would not disrupt the population dense areas that the new plans aimed to build on. The building recommenced in June 2022, when the Supreme Court rejected the writ petition. However, the <a href=\"https://www.worldbank.org/en/programs/accountability/brief/world-bank-first-dispute-resolution-service-outcome\">World Bank</a> held mediation meetings, and eventually an agreement was reached between parties, although the terms have been kept private.', 'Indigenous communities such as the Magar, Gurung and Tamang communities werwe amongst those negatively affected by the changes to the proposals for the Bharatpur-Bardaghat transmission line. According to the complaint (request for inspection) form submitted to the World Bank, the changes made to the route were done so without community members’ consent and public notification. The building of towers in these areas pose the risk of, and have effected negative impacts such as physical harm, as the transmission line passes directly through the community, and in some cases is not 5 metres away from residential homes. This increases the risk posed to the safety of the communities, and their access to public lands, sacred sites, schools etc. (three schools fall within 500 m of the transmission line). They have also had the effect of harming the biodiversity of the area, causing environmental degradation to the flora and fauna around where the towers are scheduled to be built. It is likely to cause mass displacement of communities, as they avoid the adverse impacts of the transmission line construction. Furthermore, the right to housing, and building houses on land that has traditionally belonged to indigenous communities, is in jeopardy, as building on land that has transmission lines and towers on it will non longer be viable for domestic construction in the future. All of these risks create a general risk to the livelihoods of these communities, in terms of their agricultural practices and economies affiliated with farming, that may be removed from indigenous people and their communities should the construction go ahead. Another alarming issue raised was the fact that the mandatory requirements for free prior and informed consent were not fulfilled when the locations for the towers were changed. Information regarding the project was not disseminated, meetings were not held with the affected communities, and documents were forged. Land acquisition notices were never published, and only were presented amid COVID-19, whilst a <a href=\"https://www.inspectionpanel.org/sites/default/files/cases/documents/154-Request%20for%20Inspection-Redacted-18%20October%202021.pdf\">stay order</a> from the Supreme Court was in place.', 'The affected communities appealed to the Village Development Committee to send a letter on their behalf to the Ministry of Energy to ask them to reconsider the original, less invasive route. The letter stated that the new route had adverse impacts on 96 households’, their land, agriculture, income, with increased health risks, potential displacement, and human rights violations. The VDC sent the letter to the MoE, asking them to consider building along the northeast of the Mijing River, along a route that avoided human settlement. These requests were ignored, and building went ahead without the procurement of consent, and with the use of security forces being used to suppress protests. Though there was a public hearing carried out in Kawasori, the affected community was absent due to lack of prior public notification, and the fact that the hearing took place in a different municipality to the one primarily at risk. The police forces deployed in reaction to peaceful protests against the building work have used tear gas and physical force, injuring women, senior citizens, and children. Finally, a writ petition was filed with the Supreme Court on the 6th March 2021, and building was delayed as a result, whilst the Supreme Court decided the case.  49 members of the community of Dumkibas, filed a complaint to the World Bank’s Dispute Resolution Service on 18th October 2021. They requested for the WB to address the adverse impacts they would experience through the construction of the transmission line through their community, by helping them engage in conversation and discord with the NEA.  The Supreme Court eventually ruled that building could proceed on 26th June 2022, after dismissing the writ petition, however, due to obstructions created by local dissent, building still did not commence for another year. Following the NEA’s decision to offer compensation for up to 50% of the value of the land lost to the project, this local objection has ceased, and building has resumed. However, despite the NEA’s more flexible approach to negotiations and compensation, locals are losing out on land that they still are not being properly compensated for. For example, those who have lost 75% of their land will only be compensated for 50%, those who have lost between 25% and 50% of their land will be eligible for 30% of the land\'s value as <a href=\"https://kathmandupost.com/national/2023/06/13/stalled-bharatpur-bardaghat-transmission-line-work-finally-resumes\">compensation</a>, etc.  The <a href=\"https://kathmandupost.com/national/2023/07/11/hetauda-bharatpur-power-line-comes-into-operation\">project</a> is estimated to conclude in mid-august', 'ILO Convention No. 169 (Ratified by Nepal 2007)\r\n Art 7(1) affirms the rights of Indigenous Peoples “to decide their own priorities for the process of development” and to “participate in the formulation, implementation and evaluation of plans and programmes for national and regional development which may affect them directly”\r\nArt 14 (1) mandates recognition of Indigenous Peoples “rights of ownership and possession” over the lands they “traditionally occupy.” This includes “lands not exclusively occupied by them, but to which they have traditionally had access for their subsistence and traditional activities.”\r\nDeclaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples\r\nA26- asserts the right of Indigenous Peoples to ‘the lands, territories and resources which they have traditionally owned, occupied or otherwise used or acquired’\r\nA 23 affirms the right of indigenous peoples “to determine and develop priorities and strategies for exercising their right to development.”\r\nA32 states that ‘States shall consult and cooperate in good faith with the indigenous peoples concerned through their own representative institutions in order to obtain their free and informed consent prior to the approval of any project affecting their lands or territories and other resources, particularly in connection with the development, utilization or exploitation of mineral, water or other resources’\r\nA 28(1) states that “indigenous peoples have the right to redress, by means that can include restitution or, when this is not possible, just, fair and equitable compensation, for the lands, territories and resources which they have traditionally owned or otherwise occupied or used, and which have been confiscated, taken, occupied, used or damaged without their free, prior and informed consent.”\r\nA28(2) states that  “unless otherwise freely agreed upon by the peoples concerned, compensation shall take the form of lands, territories and resources equal in quality, size and legal status or of monetary compensation or other appropriate redress.”\r\nUN Declaration on the Right to Development \r\nA1(1) defines the right to development an inalienable human right by virtue of which every human person and all peoples are entitled to participate in, contribute to, and enjoy economic, social, cultural and political development\r\nThe Constitution of Nepal\r\nA51(b)(1) requires the Nepalese Government to ‘implement international treaties, agreements to which Nepal is a party’\r\nA51(j)(8)- states the necessity to ‘make the indigenous nationalities (Aadibasi Janajati) participate in decisions concerning that community by making special provisions for opportunities and benefits in order to ensure the right of these nationalities to live with dignity, along with their identity, and protect and promote traditional knowledge, skill, culture, social tradition and experience of the indigenous nationalities and local communities’\r\nLand Acquisition Act 1977\r\nA6 Preliminary action relating to Acquire Land: \r\n(1) The officer initiating preliminary Action pursuant to Section 5 shall put a copy of notice in following office or place for the purpose of stakeholder, (a) A place where people mostly move near by the concerned land, (b) Concerned Village Development Committee and Municipality Office, (c) House door or compound wall, if house and compound wall has to be acquired.\r\n(2) The officer initiating preliminary action may enter into the concerned land or house a compound along with employee and workers for the purpose of following works after three days of Notification pursuant to Subsection (1). (a) To survey or mapping of such land, (b) To collect the sample of the soil, stone etc, to dig or boring for to find out whether the land is appropriate or not to acquire. (c) Erect pillars, etc., or otherwise demarcate lands considered suitable for acquisition, (d) Install any equipment for any of the operations mentioned in Clause (a) or (b).\r\n(3) In case it becomes necessary to cut or uproot any crop or tree on the land which is to be acquired, or to remove or demolish any wall or obstruction located therein in the course of any of the operations indicated in Clause (a to d) of Sub-Section (2), any person may do so with the approval of the officer responsible for preliminary Action, and such functions shall be performed as far as possible in the presence of the concerned person.\r\n7. Compensation for Losses : \r\n(1) Compensation shall be paid for losses resulting from clearing of crops and trees, and of demolition of walls, etc., or for damage, if any, suffered as a result of the removal or digging of earth, stone, ditches, or boring. \r\n(2) The officer responsible for preliminary Action shall determine the amount of compensation payable under Sub-Section (1) and pay the same to the concerned person.\r\n(3) In case the concerned person is not satisfied with the amount of compensation determined under Sub-Section (2), he/she may file a complaint with the chief District Officer on which he/she receives information thereof, and in such cases the decision of the Chief District Officer shall be final.', 'Gandaki Province', '$182 million', 'Magar, Gurung, Tamang, Dalits, Madnesis, Khas Arya communities', 'November 18 2021', 'The Nepal Electricity Authority, the Village Development Committee, the Ministry of Energy, the Nepali Supreme Court', 'N/A', '<a href=\"https://www.lahurnip.org/world-bank-financed-220-kv-transmission-line-project\" target=\"_blank\">LAHURNIP Report</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://kathmandupost.com/money/2019/10/15/electricity-authority-looking-for-new-contractor-to-build-transmission-line\" target=\"_blank\">The Kathmandu Post News Report</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://risingnepaldaily.com/news/13228#:~:text=The%20Bharatpur-Bardaghat%20132%20kV%20transmission%20line%20is%20separated,the%20old%20132%20KV%20line%20to%20Bardaghat%20substation\" target=\"_blank\">The Rising Nepal News Report</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://www.worldbank.org/en/programs/accountability/brief/world-bank-first-dispute-resolution-service-outcome\r\nWorld Bank Request for Inspection Form\" target=\"_blank\">World Bank Project Case</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://www.inspectionpanel.org/sites/default/files/cases/documents/154-Nepal-NIETTP-Inspection%20Panel%20Report%20and%20Recommendation-Final-16%20Feb%202022.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">World Bank Inspection Panel Report</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://kathmandupost.com/national/2023/07/11/hetauda-bharatpur-power-line-comes-into-operation\" target=\"_blank\">The Kathmandu Report</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://kathmandupost.com/national/2023/06/13/stalled-bharatpur-bardaghat-transmission-line-work-finally-resumes\" target=\"_blank\">The Kathmandu Post Report</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://www.inspectionpanel.org/sites/default/files/cases/documents/154-Request%20for%20Inspection-Redacted-18%20October%202021.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">World Bank Request for Inspection Form</a><br>', '2024-03-11 06:16:01', '2024-05-17 00:38:43'),
(13, 'Khimti-Dhalkebar 220 KV Transmission Line', '26.9500-27.4888', '85.8000-86.1071', 'The Nepal Electricity Authority project, the 220kV Power Transmission Line runs from, passing through the Sindhuli District, as well as four others.', 'The Nepal Electricity Authority project, the 220kV Power Transmission Line runs from <a href=\"https://www.accountabilitycounsel.org/client-case/nepal-high-voltage-transmission-line/#:~:text=The%20Khimti%2DDhalkebar%20220%20kV%20Transmission%20Line%20is%20a%20high,Power%20Development%20Project%20(NPDP)\">Kirnetar to Dhalkebar</a>, passing through the Sindhuli District, as well as four others.  Construction has been ongoing since 2003, however there were delays to the building process due to local dissent and protests, deferring the <a href=\"https://hpl.com.np/inauguration-of-khimti-dhalkebar-220kv-transmission-line/\">deadline</a> from 2009- 2017. The projects estimated cost is <a href=\"https://www.nea.org.np/admin/assets/uploads/supportive_docs/VCDPFinal.pdf\">$22 million</a>, with funding for the project being granted by the NEA, HMGN and the World Bank  The World Bank contributed $75 million to the project, however concerns were quickly raised regarding the violations of national and international laws, and operational policies of the World Bank itself. Chiefly, these violations centred around the lack of FPIC from indigenous communities, and the forced displacement and lack of benefit sharing that was also occurring as a <a href=\"https://www.lahurnip.org/world-bank-financed-220-kv-khimti-dhalkeber-transmission-line-project\">direct result of the construction</a>. The main communities directly and negatively affected by the project were Tamang, Megar and Newar communities, who traditionally occupied and owned the land upon which the power line was planned to be built. Throughout the construction of the project, <a href=\"https://rightsindevelopment.org/our-work/hrd/in-nepal-fighting-for-the-rights-of-indigenous-peoples/\">concerns have also been raised</a> regarding brutal and extrajudicial force used by police against peaceful protesters in order to forcibly remove them from sites in order to build upon them.', 'It is estimated that <a href=\"https://www.accountabilitycounsel.org/client-case/nepal-high-voltage-transmission-line/#:~:text=The%20Khimti%2DDhalkebar%20220%20kV%20Transmission%20Line%20is%20a%20high,Power%20Development%20Project%20(NPDP)\">114 \'000</a> people have been negatively impacted by the construction of the Khimti-Dhalkebar transmission line.  These impacts include loss of residential and urban areas to the construction sites, loss of schools, potential health and safety risks, lack of consultation or information, environmental impacts, inadequate compensation, police violence and coercion. At the project\'s initial proposal stage, the World  Bank relied on outdated data collected from a 2006 census, therefore the full extent of the impact on individuals  and communities was not appreciated. This led to <a href=\"https://www.icij.org/inside-icij/2015/07/world-bank-overlooked-families-nepal-project-panel-finds/\">unaccounted villagers losing their land</a>, with some being denied any compensation at all.   Peaceful protests were held in an attempt to persuade project enforcers to reroute the transmission line, however, in 2012, an armed police response was deployed to the site of a protest, and in the process of dismantling the protest, beat women so hard the injuries are still affecting them to this day. Similarly, in April and July 2016, armed police retaliation to a peaceful protest in the Sindhuli District resulted in the detention and beating of protesters. Both times, <a href=\"https://www.accountabilitycounsel.org/client-case/nepal-high-voltage-transmission-line/#:~:text=The%20Khimti%2DDhalkebar%20220%20kV%20Transmission%20Line%20is%20a%20high,Power%20Development%20Project%20(NPDP)\">community members were forced to sign forms</a> granting their ‘consent’ to the project before being released.', 'Attempts at advocacy have taken multiple forms. In November 2012, a peaceful protest was held, however, the police response was violent, and caused permanent damage to at least 10 protesting women. Threats of violence and intimidation from the NEA have been prevalent throughout the project building, with further police violence being utilised against a peaceful sit-in outside government offices on 10th April 2016. Direct communication from the NEA of the World Bank to the relevant communities has been sparse, often with meetings between representatives and community leaders ending with relevant concerns being dismissed. The World Bank released the project documents, which revealed that outdated data had been relied upon in the project’s conception. In January 2013, a writ petition was filed to the Supreme Court of Nepal, requesting an interim halt order against the project, and in February of the same year, a letter of concern was sent from affected communities to the World Bank, resulting in a meeting in March 2013. The government of Nepal responded to these attempts at peaceful advocacy by sending armed police forces to the construction site in order to force a resumption of the project. A second writ petition was filed to the Supreme Court in April 2013 by LAHURNIP, requesting that the land acquisition by the NEA for the road projects associated with the Transmission line be prevented. The following July, LAHURNIP and the Accountability Counsel assisted relevant communities in filing a complaint to the Inspection Panel, requesting a report be made regarding the eligibility of the project, which was issued in November of that year. The Accountability Counsel, acting on behalf of the affected community, advocated with the Inspection Panel against the World Bank, to ensure continued engagement. For example, in April 2015, the AC produced the report Livelihoods on the Line, and met with World Bank Board Members to discuss the report and further encourage a response. In July 2015, the World Bank released a report and action plan, indicating an intention to mediate with the relevant parties to reach a more beneficial agreement, through following proper process and acquiring FPIC. Throughout these advocacy attempts, threats of violence were still being made against relevant indigenous communities, therefore in July 2016, a letter and briefing paper was sent to the World Bank urging them to counter the project’s militarization. In August 2016, a letter was sent from community members to the World Bank President and Board, requesting that misrepresentations in their action plan and report be rectified. In March 2017, a facilitator was hired to oversee dialogues between the Government of Nepal and residents of Sidhuli, and in 2017 requests and appeals were made to the World Bank for an expert impartial report about conflict resolution in Nepal’s energy sector. The appeals boards demanded the release of the report by the Consensus Building Institute in October 2018. The transmission line came into operation in 2017,  despite issues raised by communities remaining unresolved, largely due to the fact that the World Bank stopped funding mediation meetings without any explanation.. However, compensation was afforded to indigenous communities.', 'ILO Convention No. 169 (Ratified by Nepal 2007)\r\n Art 7(1) affirms the rights of Indigenous Peoples “to decide their own priorities for the process of development” and to “participate in the formulation, implementation and evaluation of plans and programmes for national and regional development which may affect them directly”\r\nArt 14 (1) mandates recognition of Indigenous Peoples “rights of ownership and possession” over the lands they “traditionally occupy.” This includes “lands not exclusively occupied by them, but to which they have traditionally had access for their subsistence and traditional activities.”\r\nDeclaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples\r\nA26- asserts the right of Indigenous Peoples to ‘the lands, territories and resources which they have traditionally owned, occupied or otherwise used or acquired’\r\nA 23 affirms the right of indigenous peoples “to determine and develop priorities and strategies for exercising their right to development.”\r\nA32 tates that ‘States shall consult and cooperate in good faith with the indigenous peoples concerned through their own representative institutions in order to obtain their free and informed consent prior to the approval of any project affecting their lands or territories and other resources, particularly in connection with the development, utilization or exploitation of mineral, water or other resources’\r\nA 28(1) states that “indigenous peoples have the right to redress, by means that can include restitution or, when this is not possible, just, fair and equitable compensation, for the lands, territories and resources which they have traditionally owned or otherwise occupied or used, and which have been confiscated, taken, occupied, used or damaged without their free, prior and informed consent.”\r\nA28(2) states that t “unless otherwise freely agreed upon by the peoples concerned, compensation shall take the form of lands, territories and resources equal in quality, size and legal status or of monetary compensation or other appropriate redress.”\r\nUN Declaration on the Right to Development \r\nA1(1) defines the right to development an inalienable human right by virtue of which every human person and all peoples are entitled to participate in, contribute to, and enjoy economic, social, cultural and political development\r\nThe Constitution of Nepal\r\nA51(b)(1) requires the Nepalese Government to ‘implement international treaties, agreements to which Nepal is a party’\r\nA51(j)(8)- states the necessity to ‘make the indigenous nationalities (Aadibasi Janajati) participate in decisions concerning that community by making special provisions for opportunities and benefits in order to ensure the right of these nationalities to live with dignity, along with their identity, and protect and promote traditional knowledge, skill, culture, social tradition and experience of the indigenous nationalities and local communities’   \r\n\r\nLand Acquisition Act 1977\r\n\r\nA8. Report to be Submitted in Respect to Findings of preliminary Action: \r\n(1) The officer responsible for preliminary Action shall complete such Action within fifteen days from the starting of it, determinate whether the land is suitable for acquisition, and then submit a report containing necessary information in respect to such Action to the local office as early as possible . (2) The report to be submitted under Sub-Section (1) shall also mention the amount of compensation determined under Sub-Section (2) of Section 7, and contain full particulars of losses.\r\nA9. Notification of Land Acquisition : \r\n(1) After receiving a report of preliminary Action submitted under Section 8, the local officer shall issue a notification containing the following particulars in respect to the land. (a) The purpose for which the land is to be acquired, (b) Whether only the land is to be acquired, or whether it is to be acquired along with the houses and walls located thereon, (c) The name of the Village Development Committee and Municipality and ward number in which the land is located, (d) The plot number, if the land has already been surveyed and measured, (e) If the land has not already been surveyed and measured, such particulars as will help to identify it, and particulars regarding the boundaries thereof, (f) Area of the land, (g) Other necessary particulars\r\n(2) One copy of the notice mentioned in Sub-Section (1) shall be affixed at each of the following offices or places: (a) The local office of the project for which land is to be acquired, (b) District government office, (c) The appropriate Village Development Committee or Municipality Office, (d) The Land Revenue Office, (e) Thoroughfares Located around the concerned land, (f) Such other place as the local officer may deem appropriate. \r\n(3) In case the local officer is satisfied that the concerned person will not be able to know (about the land acquisition) notwithstanding the publication of a notice under Sub-Section (1), he/she may, if he/she so deems appropriate and feasible, personally send a notice to such person. In case the amount of compensation has already been determined by the time such notice is delivered to such person, the local officer shall also indicate in such notice the period within which he/she should appear for receiving the compensation, and the name of the office from where he/she should do so. \r\n(4) After the notice mentioned in Sub-Section (1) has been affixed, the appropriate Land Revenue Office of documents relinquishing title to the concerned land in any manner. The suspension shall be lifted in case the local officer directs the Land Administration or Revenue Office in writing to that effect.', 'Sindhuli District', '$22 million', 'Tamang, Megar and Newar communities', 'Novemeber 1 2012', 'The Supreme Court of Nepal, The Nepal Electricity Authority', 'N/A', '<a href=\"https://www.accountabilitycounsel.org/client-case/nepal-high-voltage-transmission-line/#:~:text=The%20Khimti%2DDhalkebar%20220%20kV%20Transmission%20Line%20is%20a%20high,Power%20Development%20Project%20(NPDP)\" target=\"_blank\">Accountability Council overview report</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://hpl.com.np/inauguration-of-khimti-dhalkebar-220kv-transmission-line/\" target=\"_blank\">Himal Power Limited Report</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://www.nea.org.np/admin/assets/uploads/supportive_docs/VCDPFinal.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">NEA Final Report</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://www.lahurnip.org/world-bank-financed-220-kv-khimti-dhalkeber-transmission-line-project\" target=\"_blank\">LAHURNIP Report</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://www.icij.org/inside-icij/2015/07/world-bank-overlooked-families-nepal-project-panel-finds/\" target=\"_blank\">International Consortium of Investigative Journalists</a><br>', '2024-03-11 06:20:08', '2024-03-11 22:05:14'),
(14, 'Upper Arun Hydropower Project', '27.3824', '87.2', 'The Upper Arun Hydro Electric Project is a run of river type project on the upper reach of the Arun River. The dam site will be close to the Chepuwa village, with the powerhouse being located at Chhongryang, and building of these sights is forecasted to begin in December 2023.', 'The <a href=\"http://uahel.com.np/project/1/projectDescription\">Upper Arun Hydro Electric Project</a> is a run of river type project on the upper reach of the Arun River.  The dam site will be close to the Chepuwa village, with the powerhouse being located at Chhongryang, and building of these sights is forecasted to begin in December 2023. \r\n\r\nThe World Bank has agreed to finance the preparation of the project, providing a credit of $13.1 million for preliminary <a href=\"http://uahel.com.np/project/1/projectDescription\">social and environmental studies</a> etc.  The total cost of the project is estimated to amount to $1.8 billion, and the ministry of Finance held a consultation for investment with representatives including those from World Bank, Asian Development Bank, Japan International Cooperation Agency, German Government, OPEC Fund, European Union and the European Investment Bank. In this meeting, the World Bank <a href=\"https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/donor-agencies-consulted-to-manage-investment-for-upper-arun-hydropower-project/\">expressed interest</a> in investing in the construction of the project, however, nothing has been confirmed.  The project has been awarded to the <a href=\"http://www.nepalenergyforum.com/cabinet-awarded-upper-arun-hydropower-project-to-nea/\">Upper Arun Hydro Electric Limited</a>, a subsidiary to the NEA.  The <a href=\"https://mofe.gov.np/old/noticefile/EIA_Upper%20Arun_1634889650.pdf\">project</a> is expected to impact the villages of Limbutar, Sibrun, Hema, Namase and Rukma, and will affect the indigenous communities of Bhote, Gurung, Newar, Rai, Sherpa and Tamang.  The project is also predicted to affect the natural environment and forestry surrounding and substantiating the Arun River.', 'As the project has yet to receive funding and begin its construction, the full impacts of the project are yet to be realized. However, various impact assessments have been carried out that indicate to some extent the impact we ay expect to see.  The project’s construction includes the dam and powerhouse, as well as transmission lines and a 22 km access road between the powerhouse and dam site. We can therefore anticipate the <a href=\"https://documents1.worldbank.org/curated/en/211861607316838839/pdf/Nepal-Power-Sector-Reform-and-Sustainable-Hydropower-Development-Project-Implementation-Review-and-Support-Mission-October-9-20-2020.pdf\">use and securing</a> of a large area or land.   Initial social impact assessment reports predict that the project will result in both physical and economic displacement. Of 335 households, 22 are expected to lose their homes, and <a href=\"https://www.nea.org.np/admin/assets/uploads/supportive_docs/71601820.pdf\">need to be resettled</a>.  However, economic displacement impacts could be severe, if not physical, as the <a href=\"https://pdf.usaid.gov/pdf_docs/PBAAH814.pdf\">livelihoods</a> within the proposed project area are predominantly based on agriculture, and access to cardamom and medicinal plants that grow along the river.  Furthermore, the Arun River and its tributaries serve as subsistence fishing for some indigenous communities. < a href=\"https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/start-work-on-upper-arun-hydel-project-locals\">Reportedly</a>, locals are currently enthusiastic at the prospect of the hydropower project being built and have urged the energy minister to begin the project at its earliest.  According to <a href=\"https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/start-work-on-upper-arun-hydel-project-locals\">Chair Ladar Bhote</a>, ‘the health and education sectors are likely to undergo reforms due to the project’.  However, it is worth noting that at the time of the assessments, communities were not aware of any plans to build this project, and that only immediately local individuals have been consistently made aware of the <a href=\"https://pdf.usaid.gov/pdf_docs/PBAAH814.pdf\">assessments</a> as they have been made.  Despite thus, promises have been made by both the World Bank and NEA that project affected individuals and households will be provided with financial compensation and shares in the Ikhuwa Khola hydropower project.', 'N/A', 'ILO Convention No. 169 (Ratified by Nepal 2007) Art 7(1) affirms the rights of Indigenous Peoples “to decide their own priorities for the process of development” and to “participate in the formulation, implementation and evaluation of plans and programmes for national and regional development which may affect them directly”\r\nUN Declaration on Indigenous Rights ‘A32 states that ‘States shall consult and cooperate in good faith with the indigenous peoples concerned through their own representative institutions in order to obtain their free and informed consent prior to the approval of any project affecting their lands or territories and other resources, particularly in connection with the development, utilization or exploitation of mineral, water or other resources’', 'Chepuwa Village', '$1.8 billion', 'Bhote, Gurung, Newar, Rai, Sherpa and Tamang communities', 'September 1 2015', 'NEA, Ministry for Finance', 'N/A', '<a href=\"http://uahel.com.np/project/1/projectDescription\" target=\"_blank\">Upper Arun Hydro Electric Project website report</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/donor-agencies-consulted-to-manage-investment-for-upper-arun-hydropower-project/\" target=\"_blank\">My Republica: Donor Agencies consulted to manage investment for Upper Arun Hydropower Project</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.nepalenergyforum.com/cabinet-awarded-upper-arun-hydropower-project-to-nea/\" target=\"_blank\">Nepal Energy Forum: Cabinet awarded Upper Arun Hydropower Project to NEA</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://mofe.gov.np/old/noticefile/EIA_Upper%20Arun_1634889650.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Ministry of Forests and Environment Impact Assessment</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://documents1.worldbank.org/curated/en/211861607316838839/pdf/Nepal-Power-Sector-Reform-and-Sustainable-Hydropower-Development-Project-Implementation-Review-and-Support-Mission-October-9-20-2020.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">World Bank Report</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://www.nea.org.np/admin/assets/uploads/supportive_docs/71601820.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">NEA: Resettlement Action Plan for Upper Arun Hydro Electric Project</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://pdf.usaid.gov/pdf_docs/PBAAH814.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">USAID Affirmative Investigation Document</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/start-work-on-upper-arun-hydel-project-locals\" target=\"_blank\">The Himalayan Times: Start work on Upper Arun Hydel Project: Locals</a><br>', '2024-03-11 06:27:03', '2024-05-17 00:45:44');
INSERT INTO `projects` (`id`, `project_name`, `latitude`, `longitude`, `summary`, `description`, `impacts`, `advocacies_undertaken`, `rights`, `location`, `budget`, `affected_communities`, `conflict_start`, `government_actors`, `advocacy_org`, `relevant_link`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(15, 'Arun III Hydropower Project', '27.5104505', '87.1940982', 'The Arun III is a controversial project that was initially identified by JICA in 1987, and a pre-feasibility study was carried out at that time. Despite the potential the project had, it was protested almost immediately. The project was taken over by the Nepali Congress in 1991, was redesigned in 1992 as a two-stage project', 'The Arun III is a controversial project that was initially identified by JICA in 1987, and a pre-feasibility study was carried out at that time. Despite the potential the project had, it was protested almost immediately. The project was taken over by the Nepali Congress in 1991, was redesigned in 1992 as a two-stage project, and <a href=\"https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/how-nepal-lost-arun-iii/\">initially received investment</a> from international financiers such as the World Bank.  However, the project was halted due to <a href=\"https://www.culturalsurvival.org/publications/cultural-survival-quarterly/defining-local-arun-controversy-villagers-ngos-and-world\">withdrawal of funding</a> in 1995, after it was pointed out that international environmental and human rights standards of the World Bank.  However, the project was restarted in February 2020, resulting from an agreement between Nepal and India signed in 2008.  The estimated cost of the project, through its most recent MoA, is $1.6 billion, and is being developed on a build-own-operate and transfer basis, between Arun 3 Power Development (SAPDC)- a subsidiary of Satluj Jal Vidyut Nigam, and the Government of Nepal. <a href=\"https://www.power-technology.com/projects/arun-iii-hydropower-project/\">Other financers of the project</a> are Everest Bank, Nabil Bank, State Bank of India, Punjab National Bank, Canara Bank, Union Bank of India and Export-Import Bank of India.  The <a href=\"https://www.forestpeoples.org/sites/default/files/publication/2012/12/destruction-dawnfinalnovember2012.pdf\">main site of the project</a> will be in Sankhuwasabha, and indigenous villages and communities such as Diding, Num, Sitalpati and Yaphu, which have a total population of 13’904.', 'Reactive opposition has been a definitive feature of the Arun III project. This is because concerns have been continuously raised around the fact that this project has been initiated without consultation of valid concerns raised by locals. The opposition to the initial plan came at a time when the concept of hydropower projects in Nepal, particularly those introduced with international funding, was relatively new. Therefore, miscommunications and distrust were rife, with people worried that the promise of new infrastructure and roads were not painting a full picture of the repercussions such a huge project would have on locals and their way of life. Though there was <a href=\"https://nepalstudycenter.unm.edu/MissPdfFiles/The%20Loss%20of%20Arun%20IIIRevised.pdf\">some support from locals</a> at the beginning, this was arguably because of a lack of understanding of the toll that the project would take on local ways of life and traditions.  This was not helped by the fact that by 1993, the only impact reports, prepared by the King Mahendra Trust, were difficult to locate and pay for, and were exclusively written in English. This is a clear violation of the locals right to give informed consent. Furthermore, by the time that <a href=\"https://www.culturalsurvival.org/publications/cultural-survival-quarterly/defining-local-arun-controversy-villagers-ngos-and-world\">local consultation was held</a>, the project had already begun.   Huge issue was taken with the fact that the World bank <a href=\"https://www.forestpeoples.org/sites/default/files/publication/2012/12/destruction-dawnfinalnovember2012.pdf\">assessment standards</a>, both on environmental and local impact, were not adhered to, and alternatives were not properly considered.   Alarmingly, though the World Bank pulled funding from the project, the MoU between India and Nepal signed in the resurrection of the project did not initially address any of the World Banks findings of issues and abuses associated with the project. Many of the individuals who live on the land rely on farming the land that they own and have owned for centuries. This land will be <a href=\"https://www.forestpeoples.org/sites/default/files/publication/2012/12/destruction-dawnfinalnovember2012.pdf\">submerged in the construction of the dam</a>, and the rest will be at significantly higher risks of flooding and further damage and submersion.  In fact, the risk of landslides and related natural disasters is expected to increase in Nepal, according to <a href=\"https://www.nasa.gov/feature/goddard/2020/climate-change-could-trigger-more-landslides-in-high-mountain-asia\">reports</a>.  There have been instances of land being damages in the process of the dam’s construction, with no explanation other than the activity was authorized by the state. In many of these instances, specific consent of landowners was not sought preemptively. Furthermore, the locals, particularly local women, rely on the surrounding forestry in their day to day lives. Complaints have been raised regarding the impact the project will have on the forest, and therefore, on the indigenous communities that use them in their traditions and lifestyles, such as the cultivation and harvesting of cardamom, which helps generate cash income. Finally, the locals rely on the river itself as a resource, both for fishing and for religious practice associated to the river. About 40% of locals use the river for fishing, and rely upon it for seasonal income. The river is <a href=\"https://www.forestpeoples.org/sites/default/files/publication/2012/12/destruction-dawnfinalnovember2012.pdf\">integral</a> to ritual practices within the communities, both on an individual and group level.  A large scale dam would throw all of these traditions and practices into the balance, which makes the dismissal of smaller, less impactful projects all the more alarming. Whilst project reports have been completed to a more satisfactory standard for the renewal of the project, the <a href=\" https://kathmandupost.com/national/2022/09/17/after-27-years-world-bank-returns-to-arun-river\">report made by the NEA</a> fixes compensation for 22 displaced households, and the use or damage to 2025 hectares of land.   Arguably, this does not accurately compensate all victims to the project to the full extent, as <a href=\"https://www.nea.org.np/admin/assets/uploads/supportive_docs/71601820.pdf\">studies</a> indicate that 335 households will experience loss or displacement as a result of the construction of the dam.  The compensation offered seems to have been based off the land value and not for the changes to livelihoods or other associated costs of the project that may be incurred. Furthermore, it is <a href=\"http://southasiacheck.org/in-public-interest/the-uprooted/\">reported</a> that no land for land option has been offered to those who have been displaced, instead the government, bizarrely, have promised that that will occur later on.', 'The withdrawal of the World Bank’s funding was largely brought about through local protest. The President of the World Bank at the time maintained that the decision was based on a reassessment of the problem, however, he stated that the role of the Arun Concerned Group and the Alliance for Energy was pertinent to bringing new information to the World Bank and influencing the decision.  The local protest was held on an international level, and as a result, the initial project was brought to a halt due to the fact that preliminary reporting did not align with the World Bank’s internal policies and standards.  \r\nThough, some 20 plus years later, the project seems to have had an improvement in the quality of preliminary reports surrounding its viability, there is still local dissent surrounding the way in which information has been gathered, and the lack of payout that was promised by the government. There have been protests against the project led and held by locals and indigenous communities in order to force financiers and the Nepalese government to meet local’s demands. For example, in 2008, the Indigenous Peoples Rights Forum stated that building work would be halted by protest until assurances were made by the Nepalese Government and Sutlej Corporation that their demands would be met. At the time, no such assurances had been made, however, Project Manager at the time Devandra Wardera stated that, at the time, the project was still in its survey phase, and the demands of locals would be addressed and met upon completion of the project.  However, this has not been the end of locals resorting to protests in order to have their needs acknowledged. In 2019, struggle committee president spoke at an Investment Board interaction at the District Administration Office demanding that the reality of the land use by the project be reflected properly in the compensation offered. He stated that, whilst locals were not against Arun III, they would launch a protest if the communities continued to be fed empty promises.  As a result, a five member committee was assembled to address the issue. However, in 2021, a protest was launched due to continued ineffective remedy being found to address local needs and compensation rights. Furthermore, protests have continued as recently as September 2023 against the project. Again, this is surrounding the issue of lack of proper compensation, due to a lack of funds being provided, despite promises, by the Nepali Government. A pattern has emerged of protesters being appeased with false promises and empty gestures indicating that they will be properly compensated, only for their needs to be ignored once building and construction of the project recommences.', 'ILO Convention No. 169 (Ratified by Nepal 2007)\r\n•         Art 7(1) affirms the rights of Indigenous Peoples “to decide their own priorities for the process of development” and to “participate in the formulation, implementation and evaluation of plans and programmes for national and regional development which may affect them directly”\r\n•        Art 14 (1) mandates recognition of Indigenous Peoples “rights of ownership and possession” over the lands they “traditionally occupy.” This includes “lands not exclusively occupied by them, but to which they have traditionally had access for their subsistence and traditional activities.”\r\nUN Declaration on the Rights of Indigenous People\r\n•        A 23 affirms the right of indigenous peoples “to determine and develop priorities and strategies for exercising their right to development.”\r\n•        A32 states that ‘States shall consult and cooperate in good faith with the indigenous peoples concerned through their own representative institutions in order to obtain their free and informed consent prior to the approval of any project affecting their lands or territories and other resources, particularly in connection with the development, utilization or exploitation of mineral, water or other resources’\r\n•        A 28(1) states that “indigenous peoples have the right to redress, by means that can include restitution or, when this is not possible, just, fair and equitable compensation, for the lands, territories and resources which they have traditionally owned or otherwise occupied or used, and which have been confiscated, taken, occupied, used or damaged without their free, prior and informed consent.”\r\n•        A28(2) states that  “unless otherwise freely agreed upon by the peoples concerned, compensation shall take the form of lands, territories and resources equal in quality, size and legal status or of monetary compensation or other appropriate redress.”\r\nUN Declaration on the Right to Development \r\n•        A1(1) defines the right to development an inalienable human right by virtue of which every human person and all peoples are entitled to participate in, contribute to, and enjoy economic, social, cultural and political development\r\nThe Constitution of Nepal\r\n•        A51(b)(1) requires the Nepalese Government to ‘implement international treaties, agreements to which Nepal is a party’\r\n•        A51(j)(8)- states the necessity to ‘make the indigenous nationalities (Aadibasi Janajati) participate in decisions concerning that community by making special provisions for opportunities and benefits in order to ensure the right of these nationalities to live with dignity, along with their identity, and protect and promote traditional knowledge, skill, culture, social tradition and experience of the indigenous nationalities and local communities’\r\nLand Acquisition Act 1977\r\n•        A7- (1) Compensation shall be paid for losses resulting from clearing of crops and trees, and of demolition of walls, etc., or for damage, if any, suffered as a result of the removal or digging of earth, stone, ditches, or boring. \r\n•        (3) In case the concerned person is not satisfied with the amount of compensation determined under Sub-Section (2), he/she may file a complaint with the chief District Officer on which he/she receives information thereof, and in such cases the decision of the Chief District Officer shall be final.', 'Sankhuwasabha', '$1.6 billion', 'Diding, Num, Sitalpati and Yaphu communities', '1991', 'Nepal Electricity Authority, The Government of Nepal', 'Arun Concerned Group, Alliance for Energy', '<a href=\"https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/how-nepal-lost-arun-iii/\" target=\"_blank\">My Republica: How Nepal lost Arun III</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://www.culturalsurvival.org/publications/cultural-survival-quarterly/defining-local-arun-controversy-villagers-ngos-and-world\" target=\"_blank\">Cultural Survival: Defining the “Local” in the Arun Controversy: Villagers, NGOs, and the World Bank in the Arun Valley, Nepal</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://www.power-technology.com/projects/arun-iii-hydropower-project/\" target=\"_blank\">Power Technology: Arun III Hydropower Project</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://www.forestpeoples.org/sites/default/files/publication/2012/12/destruction-dawnfinalnovember2012.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Forest Peoples Programme: Destruction at Dawn: The Rights of Indigenous Peoples in the Republic of Nepal</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://nepalstudycenter.unm.edu/MissPdfFiles/The%20Loss%20of%20Arun%20IIIRevised.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Nepal Study Centre: The Loss of Arun III, Dr Ram S. Mahat</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://www.nasa.gov/feature/goddard/2020/climate-change-could-trigger-more-landslides-in-high-mountain-asia\" target=\"_blank\">NASA TV: Climate Change Could Trigger More Landslides in High Mountain Area</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://kathmandupost.com/national/2022/09/17/after-27-years-world-bank-returns-to-arun-river\" target=\"_blank\">The Kathmandu Post: After 27 years, World Bank returns to Arun River</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://www.nea.org.np/admin/assets/uploads/supportive_docs/71601820.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">NEA: Resettlement Action Plan for Upper Arun Hydro Electric Project</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"http://southasiacheck.org/in-public-interest/the-uprooted/\" target=\"_blank\">South Asia Check: The Uprooted</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://www.iaia.org/pdf/case-studies/ArunIIIProject.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">IAIA: EIA as applied in the case of the 402 MW Arun-III Hydroelectric Project</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/threat-to-halt-arun-iii-project\" target=\"_blank\">The Himalayan Times : Threat to halt Arun III project</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://kathmandupost.com/money/2019/05/11/arun-iii-project-locals-locked-in-land-compensation-dispute\" target=\"_blank\">The Kathmandu Post: Arun III project, locals locked in land compensation dispute</a><br>', '2024-03-11 21:59:09', '2024-03-11 22:03:13'),
(16, 'Hetauda-Dhalkebar-Inaruwa 400 KV Transmission Line', '27.0838404', '85.3428859', 'In 2011, the transmission line was presented as essential for strengthening Nepal’s domestic power transmission system.  The transmission line was due to travel across Nepal, from the Hetauda Sub-metropolis-11 substation of Makwanpur and connect to Bhokraha Narasimha Rural Municipality-4 of Sunsari and will cross 10 districts.', 'The <a href=\"https://www.nea.org.np/admin/assets/uploads/supportive_docs/12305842.pdf\">Hetauda-Dhalkebar-Inaruwa 400 KV Transmission Line</a> designed to initially import energy from India into Nepal.  The transmission line is 288.km long, and <a href=\"https://www.nea.org.np/admin/assets/uploads/supportive_docs/47580641.pdf\">initial plans</a> made allowances for the construction of 792 towers.  At the <a href=\"https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/construction-of-transmission-line-stalled-for-six-years\">project’s conception</a> in 2011, the transmission line was presented as essential for strengthening Nepal’s domestic power transmission system.  The transmission line was due to travel across Nepal, from the Hetauda Sub-metropolis-11 substation of Makwanpur and connect to Bhokraha Narasimha Rural Municipality-4 of Sunsari and will cross 10 districts. Whilst the project was intended to help meet the increasing power demand in Nepal, <a href=\"https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/sc-clears-obstruction-to-transmission-lines\">delays</a> in building have led to complaints from western regions of Nepal to complain that the project has unevenly distributed these energy imports.  On the other side of this argument, however, are arguments from various communities and environmental reports, which indicate that not enough care was taken to plan the least invasive route for the transmission line. Indeed, <a href=\"https://www.urjakhabar.com/news/0603528274\">project reports</a> indicate that 50 different ethnic groups, including Bramhin, Chhetri, Tharu, and Tamang indigenous groups stand to be affected by project activity, who have therefore repeatedly demanded that the transmission line be rerouted.  Though the World Bank had initially pledged $138 million for the project, the ongoing nature of this conflict led to them withdrawing funding from the project, estimated to cost a total of $170 million. The rest of the project will be funded in its entirety by the <a href=\"https://powerline.net.in/2022/07/15/nepal-supreme-court-allows-construction-of-400-kv-hetauda-dhalkebar-inaruwa-project/\">Government of Nepal</a>', 'The project was due to be completed in 2016, however construction is still ongoing, due to <a href=\"http://www.nepalenergyforum.com/power-line-project-floundering-eight-years-into-construction/\">environmental and community impacts</a>, and poor work execution.   According to <a href=\"http://www.nepalenergyforum.com/power-line-project-floundering-eight-years-into-construction/\">initial studies</a>, 564 households were estimated to be at risk of negative impacts due to project construction, with 319 of the proposed towers intended to be built on community forest areas, and 473 on private land.  In order for such <a href=\"https://www.nea.org.np/admin/assets/uploads/supportive_docs/47580641.pdf\">construction to be feasible</a>, 131’229 trees needed to be cut down to create a path for the transmission lines, totaling 95 different species.  The plans for many of these towers were to be built in Chitwan National Park, however <a href=\"https://nepalnews.com/index.php/s/business/transmission-line-of-mcc-grants-land-acquisition-and-access-to-forests-can-be-complicated\">local protests</a> have delayed this construction.  <a href=\" https://documents1.worldbank.org/curated/en/138811629730936524/pdf/Nepal-India-Electricity-Transmission-and-Trade-Project-Resettlement-Action-Plan.pdf\">Resettlement action plans</a> have been formulated by the World Bank, which identifies and acknowledges the amount of project affected locals.  However, what is concerning is that these documents only identify 171 houses that will be affected by the Right of Way. Furthermore, the <a href=\"https://documents1.worldbank.org/curated/en/138811629730936524/pdf/Nepal-India-Electricity-Transmission-and-Trade-Project-Resettlement-Action-Plan.pdf\">compensation</a> offered to project affected locals covers 20% of the total value of the land affected.  Not only this, but the valuation of the compensation was based off land prices at the time of the project’s conception. Due to local protests, as well as contractor issues and incompetency, delays in building have occurred alongside a huge increase in land prices. This has yet to be reflected in the compensation offered to <a href=\"https://www.urjakhabar.com/news/0603528274\">locals</a>.  Finally, the project is being carried out despite continued <a href=\"https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/118287/\">protests</a> from locals.  Therefore, the lack of FPIC obtained is clear, as the project is being carried out despite lack of agreement from project affected locals.', 'The protests from locals have been a definitive element of the construction of this project. Physical disruption of the project has been one of the delaying factors of its construction. This <a href=\"https://www.urjakhabar.com/news/0603528274\">obstruction</a> prevented the construction of 40-42 towers in various locations and took so long that previously cleared forests grew back.  The project manager of the Transmission Line has responded by continuing to pursue <a href=\"http://www.nepalenergyforum.com/power-line-project-floundering-eight-years-into-construction/\">forest clearance permits</a>.   Furthermore, though some concession has been made towards negotiating with locals regarding compensation, locals are still making it clear that they want the <a href=\"https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/118287/\">transmission lines to be rerouted</a>, and for other feasible routes to be explored rather than their lands be built on and their traditions and livelihoods be impacted.  As a result of this impasse, and a lack of cooperation from the NEA and other contractors, writ petitions have been filed with the Nepal Supreme Court, by former minister Sarita Giri, on 30th January 2020, requesting that the building be stopped and rerouted. The interim order was issued accordingly, however <a href=\"https://kathmandupost.com/national/2022/07/06/court-paves-the-way-for-the-construction-of-pylons-in-hetauda-dhalkebar-inaruwa-power-line\">follow up hearings were delayed for three years</a>, partially due to the inefficiency of the Supreme Court generally, and partially due to the impacts of Covid-19.  However, the Supreme Court gave its verdict in 2023, stating that building could continue, and that the NEA only needed to grant compensation to the locals as per the compensation guidelines. The Supreme Court stated that the importance of supplying energy to Western Nepal was a <a href=\"https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/sc-clears-obstruction-to-transmission-lines\">key consideration</a> in the decision.  Whilst this is a disappointing outcome, it is relevant to consider that the World Bank, who was funding the project, has stopped the funding and soft management of the project due to the delays that have occurred due to protests, inefficient contractors, and other factors. The World Bank had extended the project deadline several times, however, due to continuous delays due to protests from locals, the <a href=\"https://kathmandupost.com/national/2022/07/06/court-paves-the-way-for-the-construction-of-pylons-in-hetauda-dhalkebar-inaruwa-power-line\">funding was discontinued</a>.  Despite this, talks still are ongoing between the managing director of the NEA, the project lead the Mayor of Hetauda Sub-metropolitan City, Ward chairs of Ward 15 and 16, to find solutions, and act more closely with India to complete the project that will enhance the energy transmission between India and Nepal.', 'ILO Convention No. 169 (Ratified by Nepal 2007)\r\n-         Art 7(1) affirms the rights of Indigenous Peoples “to decide their own priorities for the process of development” and to “participate in the formulation, implementation and evaluation of plans and programmes for national and regional development which may affect them directly”\r\n-        Art 14 (1) mandates recognition of Indigenous Peoples “rights of ownership and possession” over the lands they “traditionally occupy.” This includes “lands not exclusively occupied by them, but to which they have traditionally had access for their subsistence and traditional activities.”\r\nDeclaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples\r\n-        A26- asserts the right of Indigenous Peoples to ‘the lands, territories and resources which they have traditionally owned, occupied or otherwise used or acquired’\r\n-        A 23 affirms the right of indigenous peoples “to determine and develop priorities and strategies for exercising their right to development.”\r\n-        A32 tates that ‘States shall consult and cooperate in good faith with the indigenous peoples concerned through their own representative institutions in order to obtain their free and informed consent prior to the approval of any project affecting their lands or territories and other resources, particularly in connection with the development, utilization or exploitation of mineral, water or other resources’\r\n-        A 28(1) states that “indigenous peoples have the right to redress, by means that can include restitution or, when this is not possible, just, fair and equitable compensation, for the lands, territories and resources which they have traditionally owned or otherwise occupied or used, and which have been confiscated, taken, occupied, used or damaged without their free, prior and informed consent.”\r\n-        A28(2) states that t “unless otherwise freely agreed upon by the peoples concerned, compensation shall take the form of lands, territories and resources equal in quality, size and legal status or of monetary compensation or other appropriate redress.”\r\nUN Declaration on the Right to Development \r\n-        A1(1) defines the right to development an inalienable human right by virtue of which every human person and all peoples are entitled to participate in, contribute to, and enjoy economic, social, cultural and political development\r\nThe Constitution of Nepal\r\n-        A51(b)(1) requires the Nepalese Government to ‘implement international treaties, agreements to which Nepal is a party’\r\n-        A51(j)(8)- states the necessity to ‘make the indigenous nationalities (Aadibasi Janajati) participate in decisions concerning that community by making special provisions for opportunities and benefits in order to ensure the right of these nationalities to live with dignity, along with their identity, and protect and promote traditional knowledge, skill, culture, social tradition and experience of the indigenous nationalities and local communities’', 'From the Hetauda Sub-metropolis-11 substation of Makwanpur and connect to Bhokraha Narasimha Rural Municipality-4 of Sunsari, crossing 10 districts: Kathmandu, Sindhupalchowk, Nuwakot, Dhading, Makwanpur, Chitwan, Tanahu, Palpa, Nawalpur and Parasi', '$170 million', 'Bramhin, Chhetri, Tharu, and Tamang indigenous groups', '2011', 'Nepal Electricity Authority, Nepal Supreme Court, Ministry of Energy, Water Resources and Irrigation', 'N/A', '<a href=\"https://www.nea.org.np/admin/assets/uploads/supportive_docs/12305842.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">NEA Resettlement Action Plan of Hetauda-Dalkebar-Duhabi 400 kV TL</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://www.nea.org.np/admin/assets/uploads/supportive_docs/47580641.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">NEA Initial Environmental Examination of Hetauda-Dhalkebar-Duhabi 400 kV Transmisison Line</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/construction-of-transmission-line-stalled-for-six-years\" target=\"_blank\">The Himalayan Times: Construction of transmission line stalled for six years</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/sc-clears-obstruction-to-transmission-lines\" target=\"_blank\">The Himalayan Times: SC clears obstruction to transmission lines</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://www.urjakhabar.com/news/0603528274\" target=\"_blank\">The Kathmandu Post: World Bank pulling out of transmission line project shows challenges for MCC</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://powerline.net.in/2022/07/15/nepal-supreme-court-allows-construction-of-400-kv-hetauda-dhalkebar-inaruwa-project/\" target=\"_blank\">Powerline: Nepal Supreme Court allows construction of 400 kV Hetauda-Dhalkebar-Inaruwa project</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.nepalenergyforum.com/power-line-project-floundering-eight-years-into-construction/\" target=\"_blank\">Nepal Energy Forum: Power line project floundering eight years into construction</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://nepalnews.com/index.php/s/business/transmission-line-of-mcc-grants-land-acquisition-and-access-to-forests-can-be-complicated\" target=\"_blank\">Nepal News: Transmission Line of MCC Grant comes with land complications</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://documents1.worldbank.org/curated/en/138811629730936524/pdf/Nepal-India-Electricity-Transmission-and-Trade-Project-Resettlement-Action-Plan.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Nepal India Electricity Transmission and Trade Project Resettlement Action Plan</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/118287/\" target=\"_blank\">MyRepublica: Construction of Hetauda-Dhalkebar-Inaruwa 400 kV transmission line obstructed</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://kathmandupost.com/national/2022/07/06/court-paves-the-way-for-the-construction-of-pylons-in-hetauda-dhalkebar-inaruwa-power-line\" target=\"_blank\">The Kathmandu Post: Court paves way for construction of pylons for Hetauda-Dhalkebar-Inaruwa power line</a><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://www.tndindia.com/commissioning-of-nepals-first-400kv-gis-substation/\" target=\"_blank\">T&D India: Commissioning of Nepal’s First 400kV GIS Substation</a><br>', '2024-03-11 22:11:39', '2024-03-11 22:11:39'),
(17, 'Lapsiphedi-Ratmate transmission line (MCC)', '27.4442', '85.3033', 'The Lapsiphedi-Ratmate Lapsephedi is a transmission line that will be located in the Lapsophedi (Bojheni) region.  Specifically, it will run from Lapsiphedi, in Northeastern Kathmandu, to Ratmate in Nuwakot.', 'The Lapsiphedi-Ratmate Lapsephedi is a transmission line that will be located in the Lapsophedi (Bojheni) region.  Specifically, it will run from Lapsiphedi, in Northeastern Kathmandu, to Ratmate in Nuwakot.  This project is part of a wider scheme funded by the US aid Millenium Challenge Corporation, which aims to construct a 312 kilometer transmission line scheme, connecting Nepal with India.  Whilst little has been confirmed as to the actual amount that this particular transmission line will cost, we know that the project is made up of three key transmission lines, and the overall estimated cost of the project is 228 million.  We can therefore estimate that the cost will be roughly a third of the overall project budget, at approximately $76 million. Funding for the project will be partially funded as a result of Nepal signing an MOA with the Millennium Challenge Corporation, which created the MCC Nepal Compact. This affected area (Bojheni) is primarily home to the Tamang community and their traditions and livelihoods. Therefore, the construction of this project poses a huge risk to the community, and their rights', 'The Tamang Indigenous peoples use the lands in Bojheni to practice customary and spiritual rituals walled Choho which are nearing extension in other Tamang settlements. These practices will be threatened, as will the Tamang communities’ cultural heritage and practices. 500 households on the site of the proposed substation will be affected.   A preliminary list that has been published by Senior Officer Hari Krishna Upretty lists some 50 settlements of 18 wards that will be affected.  Furthermore, the NEA had not disclosed the plans to build a power line through the middle of the Taang settlement, even though in doing so, the constriction will displace the community that currently resides on that land. Furthermore, according to the Upper Tamakoshi Hydropower Project Victims Committee, landowners were not afforded information about the project in their native language.  According to reports, the initial planned location for the substation was Mandandeupur in Kavre, however these plans were changed without consulting locals, who were uninformed about the potential for this change of plans, nor the location of the meeting for them to voice their dissent. Locals are adamant that they do not want a substation to be built in Bojheni. Local level government has been accused of apathy towards these concerns and demands of locals.', 'Protests have been carried out against the proposed building of the transmission lines and substations in Bojheni. The NEA forcefully initiated a survey on the 1st January 2023, which was met with community protests, that lasted over a week. The response was state and police brutality, and the arrest of community members, with armed police also threatening community members at gunpoint, and manhandled and injured at least a dozen people. The Struggle Committee and Ward office have also submitted multiple forms of correspondence to the NEA and the Ministry of Energy urging them to reconsider the location of the transmission lines, however, these demands have not been effectively addressed.   The managing director of the NEA has publicly admitted that the process for obtaining consent from locals was weak. A meeting was subsequently held with affected communities and the NEA, where a three point plan was drafted to remove security forces from Bojheni, to stop the survey work until a consensus was reached, and for protests to be suspended.  However, despite a lack of consensus being watched, and the need for lands to be acquired for the project to proceed, the MCC Nepal Nepal Compact has since gone into its implementation phase, and the project has been opened for potential bids. However, it was announced in 2023 that all MCC contracts have been cancelled, due to the MCA-Nepal’s inability to procure lands in a timely manner, and concerns expressed by the finance minister regarding the unsustainably high cost of the project.', 'ILO Convention No. 169 (Ratified by Nepal 2007)\r\n-         Art 7(1) affirms the rights of Indigenous Peoples “to decide their own priorities for the process of development” and to “participate in the formulation, implementation and evaluation of plans and programmes for national and regional development which may affect them directly”\r\n-        Art 14 (1) mandates recognition of Indigenous Peoples “rights of ownership and possession” over the lands they “traditionally occupy.” This includes “lands not exclusively occupied by them, but to which they have traditionally had access for their subsistence and traditional activities.”\r\nDeclaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples\r\n-        A26- asserts the right of Indigenous Peoples to ‘the lands, territories and resources which they have traditionally owned, occupied or otherwise used or acquired’\r\n-        A 23 affirms the right of indigenous peoples “to determine and develop priorities and strategies for exercising their right to development.”\r\n-        A32 tates that ‘States shall consult and cooperate in good faith with the indigenous peoples concerned through their own representative institutions in order to obtain their free and informed consent prior to the approval of any project affecting their lands or territories and other resources, particularly in connection with the development, utilization or exploitation of mineral, water or other resources’\r\n-        A 28(1) states that “indigenous peoples have the right to redress, by means that can include restitution or, when this is not possible, just, fair and equitable compensation, for the lands, territories and resources which they have traditionally owned or otherwise occupied or used, and which have been confiscated, taken, occupied, used or damaged without their free, prior and informed consent.”\r\n-        A28(2) states that t “unless otherwise freely agreed upon by the peoples concerned, compensation shall take the form of lands, territories and resources equal in quality, size and legal status or of monetary compensation or other appropriate redress.”\r\nUN Declaration on the Right to Development \r\n-        A1(1) defines the right to development an inalienable human right by virtue of which every human person and all peoples are entitled to participate in, contribute to, and enjoy economic, social, cultural and political development\r\nThe Constitution of Nepal\r\n-        A51(b)(1) requires the Nepalese Government to ‘implement international treaties, agreements to which Nepal is a party’\r\n-        A51(j)(8)- states the necessity to ‘make the indigenous nationalities (Aadibasi Janajati) participate in decisions concerning that community by making special provisions for opportunities and benefits in order to ensure the right of these nationalities to live with dignity, along with their identity, and protect and promote traditional knowledge, skill, culture, social tradition and experience of the indigenous nationalities and local communities’', 'Lapsiphedi in Northern Kathmandu to Ratmate in Nuwakot', '$76 Million', 'Tamang Communities', '2015', 'The Ministry of Energy, The Government of Nepal', 'The Struggle Committee, The Upper Tamakoshi Hydropower Project Victims Committee', 'n/a', '2024-03-11 22:32:09', '2024-03-11 22:32:09'),
(18, 'Bheri-Babai diversion project', '28.3516', '81.72109', 'The Bheri Babai Project was listed as a National Pride project by the Government of Nepal in 2011.  It is a multipurpose project, consisting of Hydropower and Irrigation components.', 'The Bheri Babai Project was listed as a National Pride project by the Government of Nepal in 2011.  It is a multipurpose project, consisting of Hydropower and Irrigation components.   It is in Chiple, Bheriganga Municipality, Surkhet, and includes a tunnel bored through the Siwaliks mountain chain, to Hattikhal, Bardiya. The project will be funded by the Nepalese government, as has been allocated Ps 1.49 billion, which equates to $11,191,093.  The Bheri-Babai Diversion Multipurpose Project company model is endorsed by the Ministry of Energy, Water Resources, and Irrigation.  Despite being a national pride project, development has been very slow, spanning over a decade, due to natural disasters, Covid-19, and dissent from locals.  Locals in particular have continuously protested the project in areas such as Lekbesi, Bheriganga and Gurbhakot municipalities.  The Surkhet region is also home to the nomadic Raute indigenous tribe.', 'The project has been plagued with issues regarding compensation and proper recognition of project affected locals. This is due to the fact that villages have been incorrectly taken off the list of projects affected areas, following project conducted land surveys that were carried out without consulting locals.  More that one hundred families have been negatively affected by the project, despite the inaccurate findings of the project reports.  The current compensation is being offered to families whose property would be inundated by the project, however 80 families currently do not have land ownership certificates, so are being overlooked.  Furthermore, the compensation offered to locals was decided without their input. This has resulted in inadequate funds being offered even though displaced locals will lose access to their livelihoods that were traditionally derived from farming, and future employment opportunities are not secured.  Not only this, but compensation payments have been late, and oftentimes, are not paid in full.  To this day, this continues to cause uncertainty for locals. Over one hundred families in the Bheriganga, Gurbhakot and Lekbesi are yet to receive compensation.  Though this uncertainty is largely due to land ownership disputes arising from a lack of land ownership, the information Officer and Senior Divisional Engineer of the Project has stated that 22.81 hectares of land owned families who lack the accompanying documentation will be compensated.   Despite this declaration, little initiative has been taken by the Government of Nepal, who have yet to make any official decision regarding the land in question. This has added to the uncertainty locals face regarding their future homes and livelihoods', 'Landowners have formed multiple activist groups to protest the land grabs and demand accurate and timely compensation. For example, the Land Coordination Committee has been formed to advocate for those who are in danger of losing land without compensation and have generated awareness for the issue by communicating with national media outlets.   Locals have also formed a Bheri-Babai Diversion Concern Committee, with the intention of bringing all affected communities together to protest for their rights. In November 2019, a 23 point plan was submitted by the committee to the Prime Minister and Council of Ministers through the District Administration Office, in response to families being removed from the list of recognized project affected locals.   Whilst locals’ demands continue to be recognized but improperly addressed, the local protests, along with other factors such as Covid-19 and adverse weather has continuously delayed the project', 'ILO Convention No. 169 (Ratified by Nepal 2007)\r\n-        Art 7(1) affirms the rights of Indigenous Peoples “to decide their own priorities for the process of development” and to “participate in the formulation, implementation and evaluation of plans and programmes for national and regional development which may affect them directly” * \r\n-        Art 14 (1) mandates recognition of Indigenous Peoples “rights of ownership and possession” over the lands they “traditionally occupy.” This includes “lands not exclusively occupied by them, but to which they have traditionally had access for their subsistence and traditional activities.”\r\nUN Declaration on the Right to Development\r\n-         A1(1) defines the right to development an inalienable human right by virtue of which every human person and all peoples are entitled to participate in, contribute to, and enjoy economic, social, cultural and political development\r\nNepal’s Right to Information Act 2007 \r\n-        3. Right to Information: (1) Every citizen shall, subject to this Act have the right to information. (2) Every citizen shall have access to the information held in the public Bodies. (3) Notwithstanding anything provided in Sections (1) and (2), the information held by a Public Body on the following subject matters shall not be disseminated: (d) Which directly jeopardizes the harmonious relationship subsisted among various cast or communities. (e) Which interferes on individual privacy and security of body, life, property or health of a person \r\n-        4. Responsibility of a Public Body: (1) Each Public Body has to respect and protect the right to information of citizen. (2) Public Body shall have following responsibilities for the purpose of Sub-Section (1): (a) to classify and update information and make them public, publish and broadcast, (b) to make the citizens\' access to information simple and easy, (c) to conduct its functions openly and transparently, (d) to provide appropriate training and orientation to its staffs, (3) Public Body may use different national languages and mass media while publishing, broadcasting or making information public in accordance with Section (a) of Section (2). \r\nNepal Constitution \r\n-        Art 27- right to information: Every citizen shall have the right to demand and receive information on any matter of his or her interest or of public interest. Provided that no one shall be compelled to provide information on any matter which must be maintained confidential in accordance with law.\r\nLand Acquisition Act 1997 \r\n-        6. Preliminary action relating to Acquire Land: (1) The officer initiating preliminary Action pursuant to Section 5 shall put a copy of notice in following office or place for the purpose of stakeholder, (a) A place where people mostly move near by the concerned land, (b) Concerned Village Development Committee and Municipality Office, (c) House door or compound wall, if house and compound wall has to be acquired. (2) The officer initiating preliminary action may enter into the concerned land or house a compound along with employee and workers for the purpose of following works after three days of Notification pursuant to Subsection (1). (a) To survey or mapping of such land, (b) To collect the sample of the soil, stone etc, to dig or boring for to find out whether the land is appropriate or not to acquire. (c) Erect pillars, etc., or otherwise demarcate lands considered suitable for acquisition, (d) Install any equipment for any of the operations mentioned in Clause (a) or (b). (3) In case it becomes necessary to cut or uproot any crop or tree on the land which is to be acquired, or to remove or demolish any wall or obstruction located therein in the course of any of the operations indicated in Clause (a to d) of Sub-Section (2), any person may do so with the approval of the officer responsible for preliminary Action, and such functions shall be performed as far as possible in the presence of the concerned person. \r\n-        7. Compensation for Losses : (1) Compensation shall be paid for losses resulting from clearing of crops and trees, and of demolition of walls, etc., or for damage, if any, suffered as a result of the removal or digging of earth, stone, ditches, or boring. (2) The officer responsible for preliminary Action shall determine the amount of compensation payable under Sub-Section (1) and pay the same to the concerned person. (3) In case the concerned person is not satisfied with the amount of compensation determined under Sub-Section (2), he/she may file a complaint with the chief District Officer on which he/she receives information thereof, and in such cases the decision of the Chief District Officer shall be final.', 'Chiple, Bheriganga Municipality, Surkhet', '$11191093', 'Local Farmers, Raute Indigenous Community', '2013', 'Ministry of Energy, Water Resources, and Irrigation, the Prime Minister, the Council of Ministers', 'Land Coordination Committee, Bheri-Babai Diversion Concern Committee', 'myRepublica: Bheri Babai sees only 59 percent progress in 11 years\r\nhttps://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/bheri-babai-sees-only-59-percent-of-construction-in-11-years/\r\nGovernment of Nepal Ministry of Energy, Water Resources abd Irrigation Department og Water Resources and Irrigation: Bheri Babai Diversion Multipurpose Project \r\nhttps://www.bbdmp.gov.np/pages/about-project\r\nmyRepublica: National pride projects spend less than 10 percent of allocated budget\r\nhttps://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/national-pride-projects-spend-less-than-10-percent-of-allocated-budget/\r\nNepal Monitor: Farmers protest after irrigation is kept in second priority in Bheri Babai Project\r\nhttps://nepalmonitor.org/reports/view/30465\r\nThe Kathmandu Post: Bheri Babai project delayed due to damage\r\nhttps://kathmandupost.com/money/2021/09/22/bheri-babai-project-delayed-due-to-damage\r\nThe Kathmandu Post: Bheri Babai project delayed due to damage\r\nBheri Babai project delayed due to damage (kathmandupost.com)\r\nmyRepublica: Locals threaten to obstruct Bheri-Babai works\r\nhttps://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/locals-threatento-obstruct-bheri-babai-works/?categoryId=opinion\r\nThe Kathmandu Post: Families displaced by Bheri-Babai diversion project deprived of compensation\r\nhttps://kathmandupost.com/karnali-province/2021/01/08/families-displaced-by-bheri-babai-diversion-project-deprived-of-compensation#:~:text=More%20than%20a%20hundred%20families,Bheri%20Babai%20Diversion%20Multipurpose%20Project\r\nThe Rising Nepal: Bheri-Babai Project affected unable to get compensation\r\nhttps://risingnepaldaily.com/news/31058#:~:text=The%20project%20has%20distributed%20Rs,ownership%20certificates%20have%20received%20compensation\r\nThe Rising Nepal: Bheri-Babai project to take 3 more years to complete\r\nhttps://risingnepaldaily.com/news/12896', '2024-03-11 22:43:59', '2024-03-11 22:43:59');
