(20, 'Upper Karnali Hydropower Project', '28.92306', '81.47222', '<p><a href=\"https://ibn.gov.np/projects/details/upper-karnali-hydropower-3835\" target=\"_blank\">The Upper Karnali hydropower project </a>is a run of the river project&nbsp;currently in the process of development on the Karnali River. &nbsp;The site spans three districts, Surkhet, Achham and Dailekh.</p>', '<p><a href=\"https://ibn.gov.np/projects/details/upper-karnali-hydropower-3835\" target=\"_blank\">The Upper Karnali hydropower project </a>is a run of the river project&nbsp;currently in the process of development on the Karnali River. &nbsp;The site spans three districts, Surkhet, Achham and Dailekh. Once completed, the project is predicted to include a gravity dam, headrace tunnels, a fish pass, feeder tunnels, surge and pressure shafts, and silt flushing tunnels. The project has faced controversy throughout it&rsquo;s planning and finance obtaining, currently the project developers who have been granted the contract for the dam is the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://kathmandupost.com/national/2023/05/09/supreme-court-opens-for-door-gmr-to-continue-works-towards-financial-closure-to-develop-upper-karnali-hydropower-project\" target=\"_blank\">GMR Group</a>.&nbsp;&nbsp;Though the lack of funding has presented huge and continuous problems for the project, it is currently in the <a href=\"https://www.nsenergybusiness.com/projects/upper-karnali-hydropower-project-nepal\" target=\"_blank\">proposal stage for funding</a>&nbsp;from the Asian Development Bank, Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank, JICA, CDC, and Nepal Investment Bank. &nbsp;The GMR group (Grandhi Mallikarjua Rao) is an Indian company, who signed the Project Development Agreement in 2014, with the intention to export the power from Nepal to Bangladesh through India, with Nepal set to receive<a href=\"https://www.sasec.asia/index.php?page=news&amp;nid=1106&amp;url=upper-karnali-trilateral-energy&amp;enews=73\" target=\"_blank\"> 27% free equity</a>. &nbsp;The estimated cost of the project is &nbsp;$1.5 billion, however, due to continuous delays in the project, there has been little progress in terms of building or funding legitimate and updated preliminary environmental and social studies. However, we know that farmers and local fishing communities in the areas will be directly affected, such as Asarghat, Sisne, Thalpata, Surkhet, Ramaghat, Saura, Salkot and Daba.</p>', '<p>The delays in finance procurement and project progression mean that we do not know the full extent of the impact that will be felt as the result of the project. However, it is worth noting that &nbsp; the corporate social responsibility arm of GMR held a three-month training program in Delhi for locals of Karnali, who stood to be affected by the project. 16 men and 7 women were offered skills-based courses, including welding and basic computer skills. Furthermore, upstream communities reportedly are enthusiastic at the prospect of the project and the opportunities being advertised because of the project. There is a general expectation that business opportunities will be created as a result of the project, meaning migration into India would be less required for job opportunities. Though 426 stand to have their incomes from fishing and other river based activities jeopardized, there is still much support from these communities for the project to go ahead. &nbsp;Furthermore, the promise of compensation for communities whose land falls directly within the scope of the project has been offered and advertised compensation, infrastructural developments. In fact, the communities reportedly negotiated a higher price for their land than the designated government price, and initial offer from the GMR group. This set off a rush of <a href=\"https://www.sharesansar.com/newsdetail/upper-karnali-hydropower-project-sets-off-land-rush\" target=\"_blank\">buying land around the project area</a> to then sell off for a higher price to the project administrators. &nbsp; &nbsp;<br />\r\nFurther downstream is an alarmingly different story, however. There is far lower frequency contact made with the communities downstream, and the hindered river flow threatens their entire way of life, in a way that they argue cannot be accommodated for with the introduction of electricity. This impact could reach around <a href=\"https://www.thethirdpole.net/en/energy/nepal-hydropower/\" target=\"_blank\">10&rsquo;000 communities</a> downstream and could impact the biodiversity of the river and its surroundings. &nbsp;These impacts could reach communities as far as Badi village, who have stated that whikst they are currently food secure, this would impact their farming, livelihoods and ways of life. Despite this, <a href=\"https://www.thethirdpole.net/en/energy/nepal-hydropower/\" target=\"_blank\">GMR has ignored</a> their needs and demands, as they are situated far from the dam. &nbsp;This deficiency in FPIC and meaningful consultation afforded to communities who are geologically further removed from the project site, despite the detrimental impact the project will have on their land, livelihood and cultural traditions, amounts to a clear violation of indigenous rights. There is also contention regarding the compensation that was promised to communities. GMR claims that 250 families whose land was submerged was offered compensation, yet <a href=\"https://nepalitimes.com/banner/dams-and-dreams-a-journey-down-the-karnali\" target=\"_blank\">locals state</a> that few people have actually seen the money they were pledged. &nbsp;The financial trouble surrounding the project furthermore makes it seem unlikely that this compensation will be seen by its deserved recipients anytime soon. This situation has been exacerbated by reports of corruption, with the project only paying out to politically influential people. &nbsp; &nbsp;<br />\r\nFinally, worries are being expressed about the impact that, if this project goes ahead without proper environmental impact assessments, the history and quality of the river, as well as 7 native species of fish, and some 14&rsquo;826 species of insect, will be <a href=\"http://www.hakahakionline.com/en/8803/lets-join-hands-to-save-karnali-river/&quot;\" target=\"_blank\">put at risk</a>. &nbsp;The chairman of the Youth Alliance for the Environment has expressed his <a href=\"http://www.hakahakionline.com/en/8803/lets-join-hands-to-save-karnali-river/\" target=\"_blank\">concern</a> that the EIA&rsquo;s carried out have been carried out by unqualified people, and is additionally concerned that the findings of these assessments have not been made public.&nbsp;<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>', '<p>There is evidence to indicate that communities have been able to mobilize and advocate for higher compensation standards from the GMR group. Upstream, more local communities to the project, formed Upper Karnali Concern Committees in 2012, in response to the MOU signed between the Government of Nepal and the GMR in 2008, and a project report competed in 2011. These upstream UKCC&rsquo;s would reportedly <a href=\"https://www.thethirdpole.net/en/energy/nepal-hydropower/\" target=\"_blank\">mobilize</a> to protest the plans and padlock the offices, amongst other things, to force the GMR group to take their demands seriously. &nbsp; However, as mentioned, this compensation is currently incomplete in its payment, with circumstances surrounding the agreement becoming more precarious. Furthermore, for locals downstream, it was far more common to have their concerns ignored.&nbsp;<br />\r\nLocal residents of the project did however lodge a writ petition at the Supreme Court in January 2023 following the Government of Nepal&rsquo;s decision to extend the deadline for GMR to secure financial closure. This followed over a d<a href=\"https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/gmr-given-two-more-years-to-complete-financial-management-of-upper-karnali-hydro-project/\" target=\"_blank\">ecade of delays</a> and uncertainty and misinformation to locals regarding the progression of the project, and the impacts it would have. &nbsp;The Supreme Court initially issued an interim order that suspended the government&rsquo;s decision. However, the government of Nepal responded with a movement to vacate the order to allow the project to move forward. On the 7th May 2023.&nbsp;</p>', '<p><strong>ILO Convention No. 169 (Ratified by Nepal 2007)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Art 7(1) affirms the rights of Indigenous Peoples &ldquo;to decide their own priorities for the process of development&rdquo; and to &ldquo;participate in the formulation, implementation and evaluation of plans and programmes for national and regional development which may affect them directly&rdquo;</li>\r\n	<li>Art 14 (1) mandates recognition of Indigenous Peoples &ldquo;rights of ownership and possession&rdquo; over the lands they &ldquo;traditionally occupy.&rdquo; This includes &ldquo;lands not exclusively occupied by them, but to which they have traditionally had access for their subsistence and traditional activities.&rdquo;<br />\r\n	Declaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples</li>\r\n	<li>A26- asserts the right of Indigenous Peoples to &lsquo;the lands, territories and resources which they have traditionally owned, occupied or otherwise used or acquired&rsquo;</li>\r\n	<li>A 23 affirms the right of indigenous peoples &ldquo;to determine and develop priorities and strategies for exercising their right to development.&rdquo;</li>\r\n	<li>A32 tates that &lsquo;States shall consult and cooperate in good faith with the indigenous peoples concerned through their own representative institutions in order to obtain their free and informed consent prior to the approval of any project affecting their lands or territories and other resources, particularly in connection with the development, utilization or exploitation of mineral, water or other resources&rsquo;</li>\r\n	<li>A 28(1) states that &ldquo;indigenous peoples have the right to redress, by means that can include restitution or, when this is not possible, just, fair and equitable compensation, for the lands, territories and resources which they have traditionally owned or otherwise occupied or used, and which have been confiscated, taken, occupied, used or damaged without their free, prior and informed consent.&rdquo;</li>\r\n	<li>A28(2) states that t &ldquo;unless otherwise freely agreed upon by the peoples concerned, compensation shall take the form of lands, territories and resources equal in quality, size and legal status or of monetary compensation or other appropriate redress.&rdquo;</li>\r\n	<li>A1(1) defines the right to development an inalienable human right by virtue of which every human person and all peoples are entitled to participate in, contribute to, and enjoy economic, social, cultural and political development</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>The Constitution of Nepal</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A51(b)(1) requires the Nepalese Government to &lsquo;implement international treaties, agreements to which Nepal is a party&rsquo;</li>\r\n	<li>&nbsp;A51(j)(8)- states the necessity to &lsquo;make the indigenous nationalities (Aadibasi Janajati) participate in decisions concerning that community by making special provisions for opportunities and benefits in order to ensure the right of these nationalities to live with dignity, along with their identity, and protect and promote traditional knowledge, skill, culture, social tradition and experience of the indigenous nationalities and local communities&rsquo;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Surkhet, Achham and Dailekh', '$1.5 billion', 'Asarghat, Sisne, Thalpata, Surkhet, Ramaghat, Saura, Salkot and Daba', '2008', '<p>Government of Nepal,, theSupreme Court</p>', '<p>N/A</p>', '<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://ibn.gov.np/projects/details/upper-karnali-hydropower-3835\" target=\"_blank\">Investment Board Nepal Upper Karnali Project Overview</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://https://kathmandupost.com/national/2023/05/09/supreme-court-opens-for-door-gmr-to-continue-works-towards-financial-closure-to-develop-upper-karnali-hydropower-project\" target=\"_blank\">The Kathmandu Post: Court allows GMR to continue Upper Karnali financial closure works&nbsp;</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.nsenergybusiness.com/projects/upper-karnali-hydropower-project-nepal/\" target=\"_blank\">NS Energy: Upper Karnali Hydropower Project, Nepal</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.sasec.asia/index.php?page=news&amp;nid=1106&amp;url=upper-karnali-trilateral-energy&amp;enews=73\" target=\"_blank\">SASEC: DMR Energy, Bangladesh Sign PPA fir Upper Karnali Hydropower Project</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.sharesansar.com/newsdetail/upper-karnali-hydropower-project-sets-off-land-rush\" target=\"_blank\">ShareSansar: Upper Karnali Hydropower Project sets off land rush</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.thethirdpole.net/en/energy/nepal-hydropower/\" target=\"_blank\">The Third Pole: The importance of local voices in Nepal&rsquo;s hydropower projects</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://nepalitimes.com/banner/dams-and-dreams-a-journey-down-the-karnal\" target=\"_blank\">The Nepali Times: Dams and dreams a journey down the Karnali</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.hakahakionline.com/en/8803/lets-join-hands-to-save-karnali-river/\" target=\"_blank\">Hakahaki Online: Lets join hands to save the Karnali River</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/gmr-given-two-more-years-to-complete-financial-management-of-upper-karnali-hydro-project/\" target=\"_blank\">My Republica: GMR given two more years to complete financial management of Upper Karnali Hydro Project</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>', '2024-05-28 22:31:40', '2024-05-28 22:31:40'),
(21, 'Victor Simmons', '27.6866', '83.4323', '<p>sa</p>', '<p>ws</p>', '<p>s</p>', '<p>sa</p>', '<p>sa</p>', 'Alias facilis quasi', 'Consequuntur magna d', 'Quia sit sed neque', 'Ad provident optio', '<p>s</p>', '<p>ss</p>', '<p>ss</p>', '2024-05-29 05:27:25', '2024-05-29 05:28:55');

